Explanation of the Trial-System
If this task contains several trials, please use the trial system located in the left panel of the editor:

←  Factor Tree (center of the left panel):
Here you can specify the variation types for different trials in this task. Different Trial-Groups allow you to edit different frame sequences that are completely independent from each other. But keep in mind, that different Trial-Groups have the drawback that later modifications cannot be made simultanously to trials that are in different Trial-Groups. Within a Trial-Group you can specify multiple Factors each with different Levels that allow you define specific small variations between trials. If your task contains many trials with small variations between them, it is advisable to use combinations of Factors and Levels to define these small variations. If you select a Trial-Group, all modifications in the editor will effect the Default-Trial of this Trial-Group, meaning that all changes will be made to all trial variations within this Trial-Group and previously made variations will be overwritten. If you select a Level, all modifications in the editor will effect only all trials with this Level.

←  Trials & Conditions (bottom of the left panel):
Here you can see all defined Trials and Conditions based on the Factors and Levels that were specified in the "Factor Tree". Per Trial-Group you can see all Conditions, which are generated by all combinations of Factors and Levels in that Trial-Group. You can select specific Conditions here to modify small variations from the Default-Trial for this Condition. Furthermore, you can specify the number of trials (# Trials) that should be defined per Condition.

A more detailed explanation of the Trial-System can be found in the documentation under Trial-System.

Bienvenidos al experimento! Gracias por participar

Estoy investigando cómo los bilingües que hablan el inglés y el español aprenden una lengua nueva.

Hay 2 partes de este experimento:

Parte 1: español
Parte 2: francés

Durante cada parte del experimento, used va a grabar 9 palabras de una lengua. 

En la parte francés, esuchará un hablate del francés que repitirá.

Ejemplo: 
Para grabar, haga clic en el botón con el circulo. Para parar, haga clic en el boton con el circulo de nuevo. 
Para escuchar su grabación, haga clic en el botón del mitad.
Finalmente , para enviar, haga clic en el botón de la deracha con la flecha hacia arriba.

entities.name: Subject_Nr
entities.description: The variable "Subject_Nr" is a global counter of participants in a study. This can be used to do custom between subject randomization and to infer the overall number of participants in a study.

entities.name: Trial_Nr
entities.description: The variable "Trial_Nr" holds the current value of the "trial nr" for the current task. This can be used to infer whether the participant currently performs the first, second, third,(and so on) trial in this task.

entities.name: Trial_Id
entities.description: The variable "Trial_Id" holds the current value of the "trial id" for the current task. This can be used to infer which Trial is currently performed by the participant.

entities.name: Condition_Id
entities.description: The variable "Condition_Id" holds the current value of the "condition id" for the current trial. This can be used to infer which condition is currently performed by the participant.

entities.name: Subject_Code
entities.description: The variable "Subject_Code" is a unique string for each subject / session across all experiments running on Labvanced. This can be used to uniquely identify each participant or session.

entities.name: Group_Name
entities.description: The variable "Group_Name" holds the value of the "subject group name" for each participant. This can be used to infer to which subject group each participant is assigned to.

entities.name: Session_Start_Time
entities.description: The variable "Session_Start_Time" records the start time of the current participant session in UNIX time.

entities.name: Session_End_Time
entities.description: The variable "Session_End_Time" records the end time of the current participant session in UNIX time.

entities.name: Session_Name
entities.description: The variable "Session_Name" holds the value of the "session name" for the current session. This can be used to infer which session is currently performed by the participant.

entities.name: Session_Nr
entities.description: The variable "Session_Nr" holds the current value of the "session nr" for the current session. This can be used to infer whether the participant currently performs the first, second, third,(and so on) session.

entities.name: Block_Name
entities.description: The variable "Block_Name" holds the current value of the "block name" for the current session. This can be used to infer which block is currently performed by the participant.

entities.name: Block_Nr
entities.description: The variable "Bock_Nr" holds the current value of the "block nr" for the current session. This can be used to infer whether the participant currently performs the first, second, third,(and so on) block in this session.

entities.name: Task_Name
entities.description: The variable "Task_Name" holds the current value of the "task name" for the current block. This can be used to infer which task is currently performed by the participant.

entities.name: Task_Nr
entities.description: The variable "Task_Nr" holds the current value of the "task nr" for the current block. This can be used to infer whether the participant currently performs the first, second, third,(and so on) task in this block.

entities.name: TimeMeasure_Mean
entities.description: The variable "TimeMeasure_Mean" provides an estimate of the mean value of how precise callback functions work on the participants device. Hence this is a measure of how precise stimuli are be presented temporally, but not a measure of reaction time reliability (which is usually better).

entities.name: TimeMeasure_Std
entities.description: The variable "TimeMeasure_Std" provides an estimate of the standard deviation of how precise callback functions work on the participants device. Hence this is a measure of how variable stimuli presentation is temporally.

entities.name: Crowdsourcing_Code
entities.description: The variable "Crowdsourcing_Code" holds the value of the unique "crowdsourcing code", typically shown to the subject at end of the experiment to complete the crowdsourcing session and claim the payment.

entities.name: Crowdsourcing_SubjId
entities.description: The variable "Crowdsourcing_SubjId" holds the value of the unique "identification code" for each crowdsourcing participant. This can be used to later on create a reference between crowdsourcing data on Labvanced and the external crowdsourcing service (e.g Mechanical Turk).

entities.name: Subject_Nr_Per_Group
entities.description: The variable "Subject_Nr_Per_Group" is a counter per subject group in a study. This can be used to do custom between subject randomization and to infer the current number of participants within each subject group.

entities.name: Role_Id
entities.description: The variable "Role_ID" is used for multi user/multi participant studies to refer uniquely to one of the participants of the study. This can be used to present different frames and roles to different participants within the same task/experiment.

entities.name: Multi_User_Group_Id
entities.description: This variable holds a unique group ID for multi user studies.

entities.name: Displayed_Language
entities.description: The variable "Displayed Language" holds the value of the selected display language, only if there were 2 or more languages to select from. This value can be used to show different content, i.e. texts for different language settings.

entities.name: Window_Width_In_Pixels
entities.description: This variable holds the number of pixels in the X-dimension of the experiment window in pixels.

entities.name: Window_Height_In_Pixels
entities.description: This variable holds the number of pixels in the Y-dimension of the experiment window in pixels.

entities.name: Screen_Width_In_Pixels
entities.description: This variable holds the number of pixels in the X-dimension of the computer screen in pixels.

entities.name: Screen_Height_In_Pixels
entities.description: This variable holds the number of pixels in the Y-dimension of the computer screen in pixels.

entities.name: Pixel_Density_PerMM
entities.description: This variable hold the number of pixels per millimeter of the screen.

entities.name: Experiment_Version
entities.description: This variable holds the version of the experiment that is autoincremented when the study is saved.

entities.name: Browser_Spec
entities.description: The variable "Browser_Spec" holds the value of the browser used by the participant to perform the experiment. This can be used to later analyze possible differences between browsers. Allowing/forbidding certain browsers can be done via the study settings.

entities.name: System_Spec
entities.description: The variable "System_Spec" holds the value of the operating system/device used by the participant to perform the experiment. This can be used to later analyze possible differences between operating systems/devices. Allowing/forbidding certain operating systems/devices can be done via the study settings.

entities.name: Agent_Spec
entities.description: The variable "Agent_Spec" holds the complete String of the "User-Agent-Browser-Specification". This can be used to get some more detailed information about the participants system specifications.

entities.name: BrowserVersion_Spec
entities.description: The variable "BrowserVersion_Spec" holds the value of the browser version used by the participant to perform the experiment. This can be used to later analyze possible differences between browser versions.

entities.name: Is_Fullscreen
entities.description: The variable "Is_Fullscreen" is a boolean value, which indicates whether the experiment viewport is currently shown in fullscreen mode.

entities.name: Always_Fullscreen
entities.description: The variable "Always_Fullscreen", is a boolean value, which is true as long as the participant keeps the experiment running in fullscreen mode. This can be used to pause/quit the experiment when a participant leaves the fullscreen mode.

entities.name: Do you speak a third language?
Distance_To_Screen_In_CM
entities.description: This variable holds the value of the selected /adjusted distance to screen of a subject

entities.name: FaceDetectionRate
entities.description: This variable holds the value of how fast the face detection worked in detections per second.
